US Counties Coronavirus Cases and Deaths Trends¶

CA's Blueprint for a Safer Economy assigns each county to a tier based on case rate and test positivity rate. What's opened / closed under each tier.

Tiers, from most severe to least severe, categorizes coronavirus spread as widespread; substantial; moderate; or minimal.

We apply CA's tier categories to other US counties to help us understand the severity of the spread.

Related daily reports:

  1. CA counties report on cases, deaths, and hospitalizations
  2. Los Angeles County, detailed indicators
  3. Los Angeles County neighborhoods report on cases and deaths

Code available in GitHub: https://github.com/CityOfLosAngeles/covid19-indicators
Get informed with public health research

Report updated: 2/21/22; data available through 2/20/22

Cases chart, explained

Select by Major City¶

Northeast: Boston, New York City, Philadelphia, Pittsburgh, Bergen, NJ
Mid-Atlantic: Washington DC, Arlington, Fairfax, Richmond
Midwest: Chicago, Madison, Cincinnati, Lexington, Minneapolis, St Louis
Southeast: Charlotte, Columbia, Memphis, Nashville, Knoxville, Atlanta, Orlando
South: Austin, Dallas, Houston, Oklahoma City, New Orleans
West / Northwest: Portland, Seattle, Phoenix, Las Vegas, Salt Lake City, Denver, Alburquerque
California: All CA counties


Note for small values: If the 7-day rolling average of new cases or new deaths is under 10, the 7-day rolling average is listed for the past week, rather than a percent change. Given that it is a rolling average, decimals are possible, and are rounded to 1 decimal place.

Northeast¶

Boston (Suffolk, MA)¶

As of 2/20/22, there were 204,632 total cases and 2,256 total deaths.
In the past week, new cases grew by -22.4%; new deaths went from 4.4 to 5.7.
New cases are 4.4x higher than the Tier 4 cut-off. (1 = Tier 4 widespread cut-off; 2 = new cases are 2x higher than the Tier 4 cut-off).
In the past week, the doubling time went from 660 days to 784 days (longer doubling time is better).
